value_description: AB=Abnormal AH=Abnormally high  AL=Abnormally low  CH=Critically high  CL=Critically low  CR=Critical  IN=Inconclusive  NL=Normal  NI=No information  UN=Unknown  OT=Other
description: Abnormal result indicator. This value comes from the source data; do not apply logic to create it.
Arbitrary encounter-level identifier used to link across tables. This is an optional field, and should only be populated if the lab was collected as part of a healthcare encounter.

Logical Observation Identifiers, Names, and Codes (LOINC) from the Regenstrief Institute. Results with local versions of LOINC codes (e.g., LOINC candidate codes) should be included in the RAW_table field, but the LOINC variable should be set to missing. Current LOINC codes are from 3-7 characters long but Regenstrief suggests a length of 10 for future growth. The last digit of the LOINC code is a check digit and is always preceded by a hyphen. All parts of the LOINC code, including the hyphen, must be included. Do not pad the LOINC code with leading zeros. Please see the LOINC reference table for known LOINC codes for each LAB_NAME.
Date test was ordered.
Optional variable for local and standard procedure codes, used to identify the originating order for the lab test.

value_description: 09=ICD-9-PCS 10=ICD-10-PCS  11=ICD-11-PCS  CH = CPT or HCPCS  LC=LOINC  ND=NDC  RE=Revenue  NI=No information  UN=Unknown  OT=Other
description: Procedure code type, if applicable.  Value set modified in v4 to combine CPT and HCPCS codes into one category; also, ICD-9 value set item typo corrected to specify ICD-9-PCS
Arbitrary identifier for each unique LAB_RESULT_CM record. Does not need to be persistent across refreshes, and may be created by methods such as sequence or GUID.

value_description: EQ=Equal LE=Less than or equal to  LT=Less than  NO=No higher limit  NI=No information  UN=Unknown  OT=Other
description: Modifier for NORM_RANGE_HIGH values.    For numeric results one of the following needs to be true:  1) Both MODIFIER_LOW and MODIFIER_HIGH contain EQ (e.g. normal values fall in the range 40)  2) MODIFIER_LOW contains GT or GE and MODIFIER_HIGH contains NO (e.g. normal values are >3 with no upper boundary)  3) MODIFIER_HIGH contains LT or LE and MODIFIER_LOW contains NO (e.g. normal values are <=10 with no lower boundary)

value_description: EQ=Equal GE=Greater than or equal to  GT=Greater than  NO=No lower limit  NI=No information  UN=Unknown  OT=Other
description: Modifier for NORM_RANGE_LOW values.    For numeric results one of the following needs to be true:  1) Both MODIFIER_LOW and MODIFIER_HIGH contain EQ (e.g. normal values fall in the range 40)  2) MODIFIER_LOW contains GT or GE and MODIFIER_HIGH contains NO (e.g. normal values are >3 with no upper boundary)  3) MODIFIER_HIGH contains LT or LE and MODIFIER_LOW contains NO (e.g. normal values are <=10 with no lower boundary)

Upper bound of the normal range assigned by the laboratory. Value should only contain the value of the upper bound. The symbols >, <, >=, <= should be removed. For example, if the normal range for a test is >100 and <300, then "300" should be entered.

Lower bound of the normal range assigned by the laboratory. Value should only contain the value of the lower bound. The symbols >, <, >=, <= should be removed. For example, if the normal range for a test is >100 and <300, then "100" should be entered.
Arbitrary person-level identifier. Used to link across tables.

value_description: E=Expedite R=Routine  S=Stat  NI=No information  UN=Unknown OT=Other
description: Immediacy of test. The intent of this variable is to determine whether the test was obtained as part of routine care or as an emergent/urgent diagnostic test (designated as Stat or Expedite).
Local facility code that identifies the hospital or clinic. Taken from facility claims.
Local code related to an individual lab test. This variable will not be used in queries, but may be used by local programmers to associate a record with a particular LAB_NAME.
Local code related to an individual lab test. This variable will not be used in queries, but may be used by local programmers to associate a record with a particular LAB_NAME.
Local code for ordering provider department.
Local code related to a battery or panel of lab tests. This variable will not be used in queries, but may be used by local programmers to associate a record with a particular LAB_NAME.

The original test result value as seen in your source data. Values may include a decimal point, a sign or text (e.g., POSITIVE, NEGATIVE, DETECTED). The symbols >, <, >=, <= should be removed from the value and stored in the Modifier variable instead.
Original units for the result in your source data.
Result date.

value_description: L=Lab P=Point of Care NI=No information UN=Unknown OT=Other
description: Location of the test result. Point of Care locations may include anticoagulation clinic, newborn nursery, finger stick in provider office, or home. The default value is ‘L’ unless the result is Point of Care. There should not be any missing values.

value_description: EQ=Equal GE=Greater than or equal to  GT=Greater than  LE=Less than or equal to  LT=Less than  TX=Text  NI=No information  UN=Unknown OT=Other
description: Modifier for result values. Any symbols in the RAW_RESULT value should be reflected in the RESULT_MODIFIER variable. For example, if the original source data value is "<=200" then RAW_RESULT=200 and RESULT_MODIFIER=LE. If the original source data value is text then RESULT_MODIFIER=TX. If the original source data value is a numeric value then RESULT_MODIFIER=EQ.

Standardized/converted result for quantitative results. Please see the Implementation Guidance for additional details (description updated for v4). v3.1 modification: SAS data type corrected to Numeric. Number precision and scale updated in v3.1.

value_description: BORDERLINE  POSITIVE  NEGATIVE  UNDETERMINED  NI=No information  UN=Unknown OT=Other
description: Standardized result for qualitative results. This variable should be NI for quantitative results. Please see the Implementation Guidance for additional details and information on acceptable values for each qualitative LAB_NAME (description updated in v4).
Result time.
Converted/standardized units for the result.  Please see the Implementation Guidance for additional details (description updated in v4).
Date specimen was collected.
